This class implements the BADGE algorithm [1], which selects a batch by running k-means++ on per-sample gradient embeddings, which combi...\n\nTotal: 17 results from 4 sources", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9d9e02d21a85c198", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== HTML grep ===\n<head><script>document.documentElement.classList.add('js');</script>  <title>[2607.06063] Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning</title>\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.06063: Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\" />\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity classifiers. This report presents CARE-DPP, a batch active-learning acquisition method submitted to BioDCASE Active Learning for Bioacoustics 2026 challenge. The method combines class-balanced predictive uncertainty with embedding-space novelty, while a determinantal point process (DPP) objective selects a high-quality and non-redundant acquisition batch. The uncertainty-novelty balance is annealed over the annotation budget: early cycles emphasize geometric coverage, whereas later cycles increasingly exploit classifier uncertainty. To mitigate unreliable early scores, the DPP candidate pool mixes top-quality candidates with a decreasing proportion of random exploration. An adaptive acquisition schedule uses smaller batches early and larger batches later. Evaluated over five repeats on the BirdSet HSN, POW and UHH subsets and on ATBFL, CARE-DPP obtains a mean development AULC of 0.50 for macro mAP, compared with 0.46 for the official CoreSet baseline. Ablations identify DPP batch diversification and the adaptive acquisition schedule as the largest contributors.\"/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:title\" content=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:description\" content=\"Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity...\"/>\n  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Magaldi, Hugo\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Dubus, Gabriel\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/07\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/07\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.06063\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.06063\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity classifiers. This report presents CARE-DPP, a batch active-learning acquisition method submitted to BioDCASE Active Learning for Bioacoustics 2026 challenge. The method combines class-balanced predictive uncertainty with embedding-space novelty, while a determinantal point process (DPP) objective selects a high-quality and non-redundant acquisition batch. The uncertainty-novelty balance is annealed over the annotation budget: early cycles emphasize geometric coverage, whereas later cycles increasingly exploit classifier uncertainty. To mitigate unreliable early scores, the DPP candidate pool mixes top-quality candidates with a decreasing proportion of random exploration. An adaptive acquisition schedule uses smaller batches early and larger batches later. Evaluated over five repeats on the BirdSet HSN, POW and UHH subsets and on ATBFL, CARE-DPP obtains a mean development AULC of 0.50 for macro mAP, compared with 0.46 for the official CoreSet baseline. Ablations identify DPP batch diversification and the adaptive acquisition schedule as the largest contributors.\" />\n        placeholder=\"Search papers by title, author, abstract, or ID...\">\n        dc:title=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"\n    <h1 class=\"title mathjax\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Title:</span>Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning</h1>\n    <div class=\"authors\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Authors:</span><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Magaldi,+H\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hugo Magaldi</a>, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Dubus,+G\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gabriel Dubus</a></div>            <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>View a PDF of the paper titled Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning, by Hugo Magaldi and Gabriel Dubus</div>\n    <blockquote class=\"abstract mathjax\">\n            <span class=\"descriptor\">Abstract:</span>Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity classifiers. This report presents CARE-DPP, a batch active-learning acquisition method submitted to BioDCASE Active Learning for Bioacoustics 2026 challenge. The method combines class-balanced predictive uncertainty with embedding-space novelty, while a determinantal point process (DPP) objective selects a high-quality and non-redundant acquisition batch. The uncertainty-novelty balance is annealed over the annotation budget: early cycles emphasize geometric coverage, whereas later cycles increasingly exploit classifier uncertainty. To mitigate unreliable early scores, the DPP candidate pool mixes top-quality candidates with a decreasing proportion of random exploration. An adaptive acquisition schedule uses smaller batches early and larger batches later. Evaluated over five repeats on the BirdSet HSN, POW and UHH subsets and on ATBFL, CARE-DPP obtains a mean development AULC of 0.50 for macro mAP, compared with 0.46 for the official CoreSet baseline. Ablations identify DPP batch diversification and the adaptive acquisition schedule as the largest contributors.\n          <td class=\"tablecell comments mathjax\">BioDCASE Challenge 2026 - Task 4 Active learning. Ranked 2/14</td>\nView a PDF of the paper titled Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning, by Hugo Magaldi and Gabriel Dubus</div><li><a href=\"/pdf/2607.06063\" aria-describedby=\"download-button-info\" accesskey=\"f\" class=\"abs-button download-pdf\">View PDF</a></li><li><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.06063v1\" class=\"abs-button\" id=\"latexml-download-link\">HTML (experimental)</a></li><li><a href=\"/src/2607.06063\" class=\"abs-button download-eprint\">TeX Source\n  <div><h3>Bookmark</h3></div><a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"http://www.bibsonomy.org/BibtexHandler?requTask=upload&amp;url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.06063&amp;description=Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"\n  <a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"https://reddit.com/submit?url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.06063&amp;title=Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "f025f931-f17f-4bc4-a6a1-9cdd1c928784", "uuid": "41c54aa7-7e1e-45b7-9570-eec59850559f", "timestamp": "2026-07-16T08:57:07.788Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== HTML grep ===\n<head><script>document.documentElement.classList.add('js');</script>  <title>[2607.06063] Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning</title>\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.06063: Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\" />\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity classifiers. This report presents CARE-DPP, a batch active-learning acquisition method submitted to BioDCASE Active Learning for Bioacoustics 2026 challenge. The method combines class-balanced predictive uncertainty with embedding-space novelty, while a determinantal point process (DPP) objective selects a high-quality and non-redundant acquisition batch. The uncertainty-novelty balance is annealed over the annotation budget: early cycles emphasize geometric coverage, whereas later cycles increasingly exploit classifier uncertainty. To mitigate unreliable early scores, the DPP candidate pool mixes top-quality candidates with a decreasing proportion of random exploration. An adaptive acquisition schedule uses smaller batches early and larger batches later. Evaluated over five repeats on the BirdSet HSN, POW and UHH subsets and on ATBFL, CARE-DPP obtains a mean development AULC of 0.50 for macro mAP, compared with 0.46 for the official CoreSet baseline. Ablations identify DPP batch diversification and the adaptive acquisition schedule as the largest contributors.\"/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:title\" content=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:description\" content=\"Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity...\"/>\n  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Magaldi, Hugo\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Dubus, Gabriel\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/07\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/07\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.06063\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.06063\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity classifiers. This report presents CARE-DPP, a batch active-learning acquisition method submitted to BioDCASE Active Learning for Bioacoustics 2026 challenge. The method combines class-balanced predictive uncertainty with embedding-space novelty, while a determinantal point process (DPP) objective selects a high-quality and non-redundant acquisition batch. The uncertainty-novelty balance is annealed over the annotation budget: early cycles emphasize geometric coverage, whereas later cycles increasingly exploit classifier uncertainty. To mitigate unreliable early scores, the DPP candidate pool mixes top-quality candidates with a decreasing proportion of random exploration. An adaptive acquisition schedule uses smaller batches early and larger batches later. Evaluated over five repeats on the BirdSet HSN, POW and UHH subsets and on ATBFL, CARE-DPP obtains a mean development AULC of 0.50 for macro mAP, compared with 0.46 for the official CoreSet baseline. Ablations identify DPP batch diversification and the adaptive acquisition schedule as the largest contributors.\" />\n        placeholder=\"Search papers by title, author, abstract, or ID...\">\n        dc:title=\"Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"\n    <h1 class=\"title mathjax\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Title:</span>Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning</h1>\n    <div class=\"authors\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Authors:</span><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Magaldi,+H\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hugo Magaldi</a>, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Dubus,+G\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gabriel Dubus</a></div>            <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>View a PDF of the paper titled Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning, by Hugo Magaldi and Gabriel Dubus</div>\n    <blockquote class=\"abstract mathjax\">\n            <span class=\"descriptor\">Abstract:</span>Eco-acoustic monitoring generates vast volumes of audio data, making active learning a promising approach for reducing annotation effort while efficiently training reliable biodiversity classifiers. This report presents CARE-DPP, a batch active-learning acquisition method submitted to BioDCASE Active Learning for Bioacoustics 2026 challenge. The method combines class-balanced predictive uncertainty with embedding-space novelty, while a determinantal point process (DPP) objective selects a high-quality and non-redundant acquisition batch. The uncertainty-novelty balance is annealed over the annotation budget: early cycles emphasize geometric coverage, whereas later cycles increasingly exploit classifier uncertainty. To mitigate unreliable early scores, the DPP candidate pool mixes top-quality candidates with a decreasing proportion of random exploration. An adaptive acquisition schedule uses smaller batches early and larger batches later. Evaluated over five repeats on the BirdSet HSN, POW and UHH subsets and on ATBFL, CARE-DPP obtains a mean development AULC of 0.50 for macro mAP, compared with 0.46 for the official CoreSet baseline. Ablations identify DPP batch diversification and the adaptive acquisition schedule as the largest contributors.\n          <td class=\"tablecell comments mathjax\">BioDCASE Challenge 2026 - Task 4 Active learning. Ranked 2/14</td>\nView a PDF of the paper titled Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning, by Hugo Magaldi and Gabriel Dubus</div><li><a href=\"/pdf/2607.06063\" aria-describedby=\"download-button-info\" accesskey=\"f\" class=\"abs-button download-pdf\">View PDF</a></li><li><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.06063v1\" class=\"abs-button\" id=\"latexml-download-link\">HTML (experimental)</a></li><li><a href=\"/src/2607.06063\" class=\"abs-button download-eprint\">TeX Source\n  <div><h3>Bookmark</h3></div><a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"http://www.bibsonomy.org/BibtexHandler?requTask=upload&amp;url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.06063&amp;description=Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"\n  <a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"https://reddit.com/submit?url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.06063&amp;title=Determinantal point process sampling for bioacoustic active learning\"", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a2f63898723f088c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "<head><script>document.documentElement.classList.add('js');</script>  <title>[2607.04868] Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification</title>\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.04868: Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification\" />\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Active learning is a promising framework for reducing annotation costs in large-scale bioacoustic monitoring, where expert labeling is expensive and data distributions are highly heterogeneous across environments. However, existing sample selection strategies often rely on static criteria that do not adapt to the evolving reliability of model predictions during training. This limitation can lead to suboptimal exploration-exploitation trade-offs and redundant sample selection. We propose an active learning strategy for multilabel bioacoustic event classification that jointly models predictive uncertainty, embedding-space diversity, and intra-batch redundancy. The method introduces an adaptive weighting scheme that progressively shifts from diversity-driven exploration in high-uncertainty regimes toward uncertainty-driven exploitation as the model becomes more confident, reflecting the increasing reliability of the classifier. To further improve annotation efficiency, a greedy Maximum Marginal Relevance (MMR) procedure is used to enforce diversity among selected samples within each acquisition batch. We evaluate the proposed approach within the BioDCASE 2026 Task 4 active learning framework on terrestrial (BirdSet) and marine (ATBFL) benchmarks using pretrained audio embeddings and a fixed annotation budget. Experimental results show consistent improvements in learning efficiency and competitive in terms of macro mean Average Precision (mAP) and Area Under the Learning Curve (AULC) across heterogeneous acoustic domains. The gains are particularly pronounced on structured terrestrial soundscapes, while performance remains competitive under noisier marine conditions. These findings demonstrate that adaptive acquisition strategies combining uncertainty estimation, embedding-space diversity, and redundancy-aware batch construction provide an effective and robust solution for [...].\"/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:title\" content=\"Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy...\"/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:description\" content=\"Active learning is a promising framework for reducing annotation costs in large-scale bioacoustic monitoring, where expert labeling is expensive and data distributions are highly heterogeneous...\"/>\n  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Dubus, Gabriel\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Magaldi, Hugo\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Gros-Martial, Anatole\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/06\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/06\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.04868\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.04868\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Active learning is a promising framework for reducing annotation costs in large-scale bioacoustic monitoring, where expert labeling is expensive and data distributions are highly heterogeneous across environments. However, existing sample selection strategies often rely on static criteria that do not adapt to the evolving reliability of model predictions during training. This limitation can lead to suboptimal exploration-exploitation trade-offs and redundant sample selection. We propose an active learning strategy for multilabel bioacoustic event classification that jointly models predictive uncertainty, embedding-space diversity, and intra-batch redundancy. The method introduces an adaptive weighting scheme that progressively shifts from diversity-driven exploration in high-uncertainty regimes toward uncertainty-driven exploitation as the model becomes more confident, reflecting the increasing reliability of the classifier. To further improve annotation efficiency, a greedy Maximum Marginal Relevance (MMR) procedure is used to enforce diversity among selected samples within each acquisition batch. We evaluate the proposed approach within the BioDCASE 2026 Task 4 active learning framework on terrestrial (BirdSet) and marine (ATBFL) benchmarks using pretrained audio embeddings and a fixed annotation budget. Experimental results show consistent improvements in learning efficiency and competitive in terms of macro mean Average Precision (mAP) and Area Under the Learning Curve (AULC) across heterogeneous acoustic domains. The gains are particularly pronounced on structured terrestrial soundscapes, while performance remains competitive under noisier marine conditions. These findings demonstrate that adaptive acquisition strategies combining uncertainty estimation, embedding-space diversity, and redundancy-aware batch construction provide an effective and robust solution for [...].\" />\n        placeholder=\"Search papers by title, author, abstract, or ID...\">\n        dc:title=\"Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification\"\n    <h1 class=\"title mathjax\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Title:</span>Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification</h1>\n    <div class=\"authors\"><span class=\"descriptor\">Authors:</span><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Dubus,+G\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gabriel Dubus</a>, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Magaldi,+H\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hugo Magaldi</a>, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/cs?searchtype=author&amp;query=Gros-Martial,+A\" rel=\"nofollow\">Anatole Gros-Martial</a></div>            <div id=\"download-button-info\" hidden>View a PDF of the paper titled Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification, by Gabriel Dubus and 2 other authors</div>\n    <blockquote class=\"abstract mathjax\">\n            <span class=\"descriptor\">Abstract:</span>Active learning is a promising framework for reducing annotation costs in large-scale bioacoustic monitoring, where expert labeling is expensive and data distributions are highly heterogeneous across environments. However, existing sample selection strategies often rely on static criteria that do not adapt to the evolving reliability of model predictions during training. This limitation can lead to suboptimal exploration-exploitation trade-offs and redundant sample selection. We propose an active learning strategy for multilabel bioacoustic event classification that jointly models predictive uncertainty, embedding-space diversity, and intra-batch redundancy. The method introduces an adaptive weighting scheme that progressively shifts from diversity-driven exploration in high-uncertainty regimes toward uncertainty-driven exploitation as the model becomes more confident, reflecting the increasing reliability of the classifier. To further improve annotation efficiency, a greedy Maximum Marginal Relevance (MMR) procedure is used to enforce diversity among selected samples within each acquisition batch. We evaluate the proposed approach within the BioDCASE 2026 Task 4 active learning framework on terrestrial (BirdSet) and marine (ATBFL) benchmarks using pretrained audio embeddings and a fixed annotation budget. Experimental results show consistent improvements in learning efficiency and competitive in terms of macro mean Average Precision (mAP) and Area Under the Learning Curve (AULC) across heterogeneous acoustic domains. The gains are particularly pronounced on structured terrestrial soundscapes, while performance remains competitive under noisier marine conditions. These findings demonstrate that adaptive acquisition strategies combining uncertainty estimation, embedding-space diversity, and redundancy-aware batch construction provide an effective and robust solution for [...].\n          <td class=\"tablecell comments mathjax\">BioDCASE 2026 Challenge, Task 4: Active Learning for Bioacoustics, 1st Place (1/14)</td>\nView a PDF of the paper titled Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification, by Gabriel Dubus and 2 other authors</div><li><a href=\"/pdf/2607.04868\" aria-describedby=\"download-button-info\" accesskey=\"f\" class=\"abs-button download-pdf\">View PDF</a></li><li><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.04868v1\" class=\"abs-button\" id=\"latexml-download-link\">HTML (experimental)</a></li><li><a href=\"/src/2607.04868\" class=\"abs-button download-eprint\">TeX Source\n  <div><h3>Bookmark</h3></div><a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"http://www.bibsonomy.org/BibtexHandler?requTask=upload&amp;url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.04868&amp;description=Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification\"\n  <a class=\"abs-button abs-button-grey abs-button-small\" href=\"https://reddit.com/submit?url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.04868&amp;title=Adaptive Diversity-Uncertainty Active Learning with Redundancy Control for Bioacoustic Event Classification\"", "i